%T A394689 38,57,48,40,50,44,55,60,46,69,54,52,65,70,58,87,63,77,66,62,93,72,68,
%U A394689 85,75,78,74,111,84,76,95,80,82,123,90,86,129,96,88,99,102
%N A394689 Lexicographically earliest infinite sequence of distinct positive numbers such that, for n > 2, a(n) shares a factor with a(n-1) while the set of distinct prime factors shared between a(n) and a(n-1) differs from that shared between a(n-1) and a(n-2).
%C A394689 As the sequence is infinite, no term beyond a(2) can be a prime or prime power as that would make the set of shared distinct prime factors between a(n) = p^k and a(n-1) equal {p}, which would be the same as that shared between a(n+1) and a(n).
%C A394689 In the first 10^5 terms there are no fixed points other than the first two terms, and it is likely no more exist. The sequence is conjectured to contain all numbers other than the prime powers.
%H A394689 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A394689/b394689.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%e A394689 a(4) = 12 as 12 shares a factor with a(3) = 12 while the set of distinct prime factors shared between 6 and 12 is {2,3}, which differs from the set {2}, that shared between a(3) = 6 and a(2) = 2.
%Y A394689 Cf. A064413, A000961, A027748, A392505.
